node.text:
🇪🇸 Hikers in Spain are treated to ancient ruins, historical towns, old churches and even random castles along the way. ⁠
⁠
🇪🇸 Sculpted by extensive mountain ranges surrounding a high inland plateau, Spain has nearly 6000 kilometers (3728 miles) of coastline. ⁠This means that hikers can enjoy everything from rugged cliff sides and snow capped mountains to glacial lakes and turquoise water with white sand beaches. 
⁠
📍 Albarracin,Spain 

Here is a rundown of Spain's 5 hiking routes that show off the incredibly diverse beauty of this Iberian destination.⁠
⁠
Which one do you want to do? Let us know in the comments.⁠
⁠
🥾 Peñalara⁠
Best hike for viewing glacial lakes⁠
14 km (8.7 miles), 4 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 El Caminito del Rey ⁠
Best steep trail with archaeological highlights⁠
8 km (1.9 miles), 2.5 hours, easy⁠
⁠
🥾 La Pedriza⁠
Best hike for rugged mountains⁠
12km (7.5 miles), 3 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 Cares Trail (Picos de Europa National Park)⁠
Best hike for dramatic scenery⁠
21.9 km, 6.5 hours, intermediate⁠
⁠
🥾 Camino de Santiago (French Way)⁠
Best historic hike to retrace pilgrims’ footsteps⁠
100 km (62 miles), 7 days, intermediate to difficult

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Khao Sok National Park. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
💚 Could you use some serenity when you're finally able to take that big trip?⁠
⁠
🎍 How does the exploring the giant bamboo forest in Khao Sok National Park, Thailand sound?⁠
⁠
At the heart of this jaw-droppingly beautiful national park is the Cheow Lan Lake, an artificial reservoir created in the early 1980s by damming the nearby Klong Saeng River for an electricity project. ⁠
⁠
The vast lake measures more than 70 sq mi (180 sq km) in size, and is hemmed by towering karst and limestone outcrops along the water’s edge. ⁠
⁠
Some contend that the thick evergreen vegetation covering these hills may well count as one of the oldest rainforests in the world. ⁠
⁠
Clusters of stilted eco-huts located in remote valley gaps – outfitted with nothing but the most basic amenities – offer an unparalleled overnighting experience on the reservoir’s waters. If that’s not enough, you can go canoeing on the placid expanse of the lake, or plod along primeval forest trails in search of elephants, bears, leopards and even the smelly rafflesia flower when it blooms between October and December. ⁠
⁠
The Sok River, which trickles quietly through the gorgeous scenery, is an excellent backdrop for some laid-back river rafting. The national park is a short drive from Surat Thani, which is connected to Bangkok by a quick flight.⁠
⁠
💚 Add this to your inspo folder for when it's time for you to travel again.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Glacier National Park. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
🏔 Montana has something for everyone looking to take a walk through nature. ⁠
⁠
🥾 Naturally, many outdoor enthusiasts find themselves drawn specifically to iconic Glacier National Park, which is home to most of the best hikes in the state. ⁠
⁠
🐻 Besides being home to the largest concentration of grizzly bears on the planet, tons of moose and herds of bighorn sheep, Glacier is basically a one-stop-shop of trailheads taking hikers to magnificent destinations of varying difficulty. ⁠
⁠
📝 Put Montana on your list of hiking destinations, tap the link in our bio to explore our favorite hikes and keep these tips in mind for your next adventure.⁠
⁠
🏆 Pro tips for hiking in Montana:⁠
⁠
The intense winters of the region will limit hiking (without snowshoes) to the warmer months, roughly between April and October.⁠
⁠
The weather can change quickly, dress in layers and bring rain gear and a hat.⁠
⁠
Stay hydrated and make sure to bring plenty of water with you. Throw in some snacks packed with protein and carbs as well. ⁠
⁠
Be sure to bring a trail map, compass and flashlight (don’t depend on your cell).⁠
⁠
Montana’s wilderness is rich with wildlife, so take every precaution to avoid human-animal conflicts. Make noise on the trail to let them know you're coming and carry bear spray.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Lonely Planet in Prague, Czech Republic. May be an image of outdoors and monument.

node.text:
Did you know Prague was recently named the 13th greenest city in the world?⁠
⁠
Even though you might imagine a densely packed, medieval cityscape of towers and castles, the Czech capital is actually surprisingly green. ⁠
⁠
There are plenty of places to throw down a blanket and rest your feet from the trying cobblestones. Many parks and gardens offer breathtaking views of the city, and a few even toss in the added bonus of restorative, on-site beer gardens.⁠
⁠
🍻 Who is in the mood for a sunny, green afternoon in a park in Prague? Tap the link in our bio to find all of our favorites.

node.text:
Parque Nacional da Peneda-Gerês in Portugal is just one of the day trips we recommend if you call Porto home base. ⁠
⁠
Save this to your inspo folder and tag your travel partner for when you plan your Portugal trip.⁠
⁠
📝 What to expect:⁠
The park covers a series of mountain ranges and spills over the Spanish border. Narrow roads twist through a rapidly changing landscape, which includes granite boulders, dense pine forests and stunning river views. ⁠
⁠
👀 What you'll see:⁠
A series of small towns are scattered throughout the park. This includes Lindoso, where you can see a 13th-century castle that played a key role in Portugal’s restoration wars and has since been declared a national monument. Nearby is Soajo, which, similar to Lindoso, has rows of espigueiros – little granite buildings that were elevated to keep water and mice out of the local grain supply. They’re adorable.⁠
⁠
🗺 How to get to Parque Nacional da Peneda-Gerês: ⁠
Public transport is scarce in Gerês, so hire a car or join a guided tour.⁠
⁠
⭐️ Pro tips: ⁠
Anywhere you see miradouro on a map is a viewpoint, and likely a good one. ⁠
⁠
Pack a swimsuit. There are numerous hiking trails and pools of crystal clear water to dip into afterwards. ⁠
⁠

node.text:
🏔 The mountains are always calling in Switzerland. 

Did you know that the 62,500km of trails in Switzerland would be enough to wrap around the globe 1.5 times?

We just set out to pick some of our favorite hikes in Switzerland. Want to see more? Save this to your inspo folder and tap the link in our bio. 

 Faulhornweg
🏆 Best day hike - 15km; 4½ to 5½ hours

Mother Nature pulled out all the stops in the Bernese Oberland and this is the Holy Grail of day hikes. This moderately challenging ridge hike throws you in the scenic deep end. You’ll take in the full glittering sweep of Lakes Thun and Brienz trudging from Schynige Platte to First, and colossal peaks like the dagger-shaped Wetterhorn and the big three of Eiger, Mönch and Jungfrau. 

Lakes of Macun, Swiss National Park 
🏆 Best national park hike - 22km; 7½ to 8½ hours

For a glimpse of the Swiss Alps before the dawn of tourism, there’s no place like the nature-gone-wild Swiss National Park in The Engadine in Graubünden, where Switzerland muscles its way into Italy. Squished into a remote corner of the country’s southeast, this off-the-radar national park punches high on every level, and is often so silent that the only sound is your own footsteps.

Via Alpina
🏆 Best multi-day hike - 390km; 20 days 

The Via Alpina is the big one: an epic 20-stage trek taking you from the castle-topped principality of Liechtenstein in the east to Montreux, dreamily set on the shores of Lake Geneva, in the west. Embarking on the whole thing is a serious undertaking: you’ll need to be surefooted, have a good head for heights and experience in navigating using a map and compass, as you’ll be grappling with 14 Alpine passes.

Rigi Panorama Trail
🏆  Best accessible hike - 7km; 2 hours

Following a wide path that shadows the old Scheidegg Railway, this wheelchair- and stroller-accessible ridge trail from Rigi First to Rigi Scheidegg beautifully opens up the surrounding lakes, cow-grazed pastures and mountains, with plenty of options to pause for a picnic or barbecue en route. Some sections are steep for wheelchairs (you’ll need good brakes), but there are options to shorten the trail should you so wish.

node.text:
Can you name the most photographed lighthouse in Canada?⁠
⁠
Although Peggy’s Cove Lighthouse (also known as Peggy’s Point Lighthouse) is one of the most photogenic lighthouses and one of best places to visit in Nova Scotia, if you just roam the coast, you’ll spot quite a few of the 170+ Nova Scotian lighthouses.⁠
⁠
If you want to go lighthouse spotting here are a few of our favorite ways to enjoy this iconic maritime beacon. ⁠
⁠
⭐️ Catch a sunset by Cape George Point Lighthouse, on a clear day you can see both Prince Edward Island and Cape Breton Island from atop the point.⁠
⁠
⭐️ Visit the Fortress of Louisbourg and keep an eye out for the one there that replaced the original, which was lost during the famous battles between the French and the English. ⁠
⁠
⭐️ Be sure to pop in to the Out of the Fog Lighthouse Museum on Half Island Cove.

node.text:
The Azores might be the remote escape you are looking for.⁠
⁠
For in-the-know travelers, Portugal's Azores islands have long been on the bucket list of intriguing destinations.⁠
⁠
Most people, however, still know little, if anything, about this far-flung archipelago in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean. ⁠
⁠
It's time to change that. ⁠
The Azores are a dream come true for nature lovers, fans of adventure sports or anyone looking for a sustainable destination. ⁠
⁠
🐳 🚣‍♂️ ⛰⁠
From whale watching to exploring a geological wonder world of fumaroles, mudpots, scalding springs,  caverns, and lava tubes to windsurfing, kayaking and stand up paddle boarding, these islands are pretty incredible.⁠
⁠
Tap the link in our bio to find why you should make the Azores next on your travel destination list.

node.text:
One of the most unique train rides in Thailand is a short, workaday, commuter line. ⁠
⁠
It begins near Bangkok and famously terminates smack dab in the middle of a wet market. ⁠
⁠
Sound like something you're up for? Save this to your travel inspo folder and tag your best travel mate.⁠
⁠
Here's how to make it happen:⁠
⁠
It's named the Mahachai Line⁠
🏁 Start – Thonburi⁠
🛑 End – Samut Songkhram⁠
Distance – 50 miles/80km⁠
⁠
Start at Thonburi’s Wongwian Yai train station, just across the Chao Phraya River from Bangkok, where hourly trains go to Samut Sakhon (known by locals as Mahachai). ⁠
⁠
What to expect: From the window you can peek into homes, temples and shops built an arm’s length from the passing trains. Further on you'll start to see palm trees, patchwork rice fields and marshes filled with giant elephant ear perennials and canna lilies.⁠
⁠
Next: The farms will disappear as you enter Samut Sakhon. After disembarking and walking through one of the most hectic fresh markets in the country, you’ll reach a harbour clogged with water hyacinths and wooden fishing boats. ⁠
⁠
Now it's time to: Take the ferry across to Baan Laem, where you'll board yet another train, this time for  Samut Songkhram. ⁠
⁠
When it's over: You’ll emerge directly into a hubbub of hectic market stalls. Between train arrivals and departures these stalls are set up directly on the tracks and must be hurriedly cleared away when the train arrives. It’s an amazing scene.

💙 Chefchaouen, Morocco 💙

Getting lost in the blue-washed lanes of the artsy medina became a favorite past time of LP staffer @amanda_mccadams during her visit. 

🗣In her words, “It was so easy to wander around for hours here.  The medina is not as large and intimidating as Fez or Marrakesh so I wasn’t worried about getting too turned around. My advice for travelers is to definitely give yourself plenty of time to just walk around and explore. The blue walls really are everywhere and even though you’ve seen lots of photos and have read about this being the “blue city,” experiencing it for yourself still feels really unique.”

node.text:
🥾 Looking for a remote and unspoiled hike with some of the most spectacular trails and views in the world?⁠
⁠
The Vermilion Cliffs National Monument in Arizona is it.⁠
⁠
The monument contains several diverse landscapes, including the Paria Plateau, Vermilion Cliffs, Coyote Buttes (also known as The Wave), and Paria Canyon.⁠
⁠
Don't worry about it getting too popular and overrun by tourists either. There are no paved roads within the monument and while House Rock Valley Road is a maintained dirt road, it might be impassable when wet. You'll need a four-wheel-drive, high clearance vehicle on other roads due to deep sand. ⁠
⁠
Oh, and you must have a permit for most of the spots and there are only a certain number of those available per day. ⁠
⁠
How does this sound? Let us know in the comments if you're ready for an adventure like this. ⁠
